      <div class="sx-summary-specs">
        <div class="sx-summary-spec">
          <span class="sx-spec-key">Film</span>
          <span class="sx-spec-val">SX-70 &amp; 600</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sx-summary-spec">
          <span class="sx-spec-key">Board</span>
          <span class="sx-spec-val">OpenSX70</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sx-summary-spec">
          <span class="sx-spec-key">Condition</span>
          <span class="sx-spec-val">Restored, Calibrated &amp; Upgraded</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="sx-summary-line">{{ section.settings.intro_text | default: "Every SX-70 we restore is a complete rebuild &mdash; full mechanical and optical service, and our exclusive OpenSX70 board. Incredible low-light metering, hold-to-eject, and a 6-month warranty come standard." }}</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  {%- comment -%} ════════════════════════════════════════════════
       BOARD CHAPTER — Everything about the OpenSX70 modification
       Collapsible: short intro by default, "Learn More" reveals all sections
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════ {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="sx-chapter" id="sx-chapter">
    <div class="sx-chapter-header">
      <span class="sx-chapter-eyebrow">BFC Exclusive · Inside Every Camera</span>
      <h2 class="sx-chapter-title">The OpenSX70 <em>Modification</em></h2>
      <p class="sx-chapter-sub">Every SX-70 we restore is fitted with our exclusive OpenSX70 board: It brings accurate metering, low-light capability, and hold-to-eject control to a camera that was engineered before the microprocessor existed.</p>
      <button type="button" class="sx-chapter-toggle" id="sx-chapter-toggle" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="sx-chapter-body" onclick="sxToggleChapter()">
        <span class="sx-chapter-toggle-text">Learn how it works</span>
        <svg class="sx-chapter-toggle-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 14 14" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
          <path d="M3.5 5.5L7 9L10.5 5.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </button>
    </div>

    <div class="sx-chapter-body" id="sx-chapter-body">

      {%- comment -%} ── IN-CHAPTER SUB-TABS ──
           Horizontal nav strip pinned to the top of the expanded chapter body.
           Smooth-scrolls within the chapter only. Top-level sticky TOC handles
           page-wide nav; these handle the chapter's internal sections.
           {%- endcomment -%}
      <div class="sx-subtoc" id="sx-subtoc" aria-label="OpenSX70 chapter navigation">
        <div class="sx-subtoc-inner">
          <a href="#sx-schematic" data-subtoc="schematic" class="is-active">Schematic</a>
          <a href="#sx-features" data-subtoc="features">Built In</a>
          <a href="#sx-dongle" data-subtoc="dongle">With Dongle</a>
          <a href="#sx-led-ref" data-subtoc="led-ref">LED Reference</a>
        </div>
      </div>

  {%- comment -%} ── OPENSX70 SCHEMATIC ──
      Interactive annotated drawing of the OpenSX70 board. Replaces the
      original static intro+photo. Hotspots are configured via section blocks
      of type "schematic_hotspot" — see schema at end of file. Each hotspot
      has x/y position (% of the photo), a numeric label, component name,
      tech readout, and body sentence.

      The whole block is scoped to .sx-sch-* classes so it can coexist with
      the older .sx-osx-* styles (which are no longer used by this section
      but may be referenced elsewhere). All styles, animations, and JS for
      this section live below in this file. {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="sx-sch{% unless section.settings.schematic_panels_boxed %} sx-sch--bare{% endunless %}"
       data-sx-sch
       {% if section.settings.schematic_auto_preview %}data-sx-sch-auto-preview="true"{% endif %}>

    {%- comment -%} Chapter intro: eyebrow + headline + lead paragraph.
        Replaces the old multi-paragraph copy with a single tighter setup. {%- endcomment -%}
    <div class="sx-sch-intro" id="sx-schematic" data-sx-sch-reveal="0">
      <h3 class="sx-sch-intro-title">The OpenSX70 <em>Modification.</em></h3>
      <p class="sx-sch-intro-lead">{{ section.settings.schematic_lead | default: "Every SX-70 we restore gets our exclusive OpenSX70 motherboard. Modern electronics, accurate analog metering, full film compatibility, optional manual control. A camera from 1972, working the way Polaroid intended more than 50 years later." }}</p>
    </div>

    {%- comment -%} The schematic frame itself: cream container with dot grid,
        header strip, photo with floating numbered hotspots and bare labels,
        click-to-popout panels, footer credit strip. {%- endcomment -%}
    <div class="sx-sch-frame" data-sx-sch-reveal="380">

      <div class="sx-sch-grid"></div>

      <div class="sx-sch-frame-inner">

        <div class="sx-sch-head">
          <div>
            <div class="sx-sch-head-title">A modern brain for a <em>50-year-old camera.</em></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        {%- comment -%} Photo + overlays. Padding is generous (top/bottom)
            because that's where the bare labels and popout panels live. {%- endcomment -%}
        <div class="sx-sch-stage" data-sx-sch-stage>

          <div class="sx-sch-photo">
            {%- if section.settings.schematic_image != blank -%}
              {%- comment -%} Serve the schematic at high resolution. The
                  CSS-rendered max-width is well under 1000px, but the image
                  is critical detail (a circuit board); we want crisp 2x/3x
                  retina rendering, hence the srcset and the 2400px base. {%- endcomment -%}
              <img src="{{ section.settings.schematic_image | image_url: width: 2400 }}"
                   srcset="{{ section.settings.schematic_image | image_url: width: 1200 }} 1200w,
                           {{ section.settings.schematic_image | image_url: width: 1800 }} 1800w,
                           {{ section.settings.schematic_image | image_url: width: 2400 }} 2400w,
                           {{ section.settings.schematic_image | image_url: width: 3000 }} 3000w"
                   sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px"
                   alt="OpenSX70 board"
                   loading="lazy"
                   width="{{ section.settings.schematic_image.width }}"
                   height="{{ section.settings.schematic_image.height }}">
            {%- elsif section.settings.board_image != blank -%}
              {%- comment -%} Fallback to the older board_image setting if the
                  new schematic_image isn't picked yet. {%- endcomment -%}
              <img src="{{ section.settings.board_image | image_url: width: 2400 }}"
                   srcset="{{ section.settings.board_image | image_url: width: 1200 }} 1200w,
                           {{ section.settings.board_image | image_url: width: 1800 }} 1800w,
                           {{ section.settings.board_image | image_url: width: 2400 }} 2400w"
                   sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px"
                   alt="OpenSX70 board"
                   loading="lazy">
            {%- else -%}
              <div class="sx-sch-photo-placeholder">[ Add a board photo via the theme editor ]</div>
            {%- endif -%}
          </div>

          {%- comment -%} Hotspots + bare labels + popout panels.
              Each hotspot block in the section becomes a triple of: a
              numbered dot (positioned absolutely), a bare floating label
              with a leader line, and a click-out panel that pops above
              or below the label. The "side" setting controls whether the
              label sits above or below the photo. {%- endcomment -%}
          {%- comment -%} Single full-frame SVG overlay containing one path per
              hotspot. Using one SVG (rather than per-hotspot column SVGs)
              lets each path go anywhere within the frame — necessary for
              L-shapes that travel both vertically and horizontally.

              The viewBox is 100×100 with preserveAspectRatio="none" so SVG
              units map directly to percentages of the frame's rendered
              dimensions: x=0 is left edge, x=100 is right, y=0 is top,
              y=100 is bottom. Each path uses these percentage coordinates
              directly. {%- endcomment -%}
          <svg class="sx-sch-paths"
               viewBox="0 0 100 100"
               preserveAspectRatio="none"
               aria-hidden="true">
            {%- for block in section.blocks -%}
              {%- if block.type == 'schematic_hotspot' -%}
                {%- assign hs_x      = block.settings.x_pct | default: 50 -%}
                {%- assign hs_y      = block.settings.y_pct | default: 50 -%}
                {%- assign desc_x    = block.settings.desc_x_pct | default: 50 -%}
                {%- assign desc_y    = block.settings.desc_y_pct | default: 8 -%}
                {%- comment -%} If the user hasn't moved the desc_x slider off
                    its default (50) and the dot itself isn't at 50, treat it
                    as "no override" and inherit the dot's X. This keeps newly-
                    added hotspots looking sane out of the box. {%- endcomment -%}
                {%- if desc_x == 50 and hs_x != 50 -%}
                  {%- assign desc_x = hs_x -%}
                {%- endif -%}

                {%- comment -%} ── Clamp desc_x to a safe in-frame range ──
                    Previously we used CSS `left: 8px` to pin labels/panels
                    when desc_x was too extreme. That worked visually but
                    caused the leader line to land at the user's raw
                    desc_x (e.g. 5%) while the panel sat at 8px (~1%) —
                    they didn't line up.

                    Now we clamp the desc_x value itself BEFORE any
                    positioning. The line, label, and panel all use this
                    one clamped value so they automatically align — same
                    as how an unclamped hotspot ("01") lines up perfectly. {%- endcomment -%}
                {%- if desc_x < 14 -%}
                  {%- assign desc_x = 14 -%}
                {%- elsif desc_x > 86 -%}
                  {%- assign desc_x = 86 -%}
                {%- endif -%}
                {%- assign path_desc_x = desc_x -%}

                {%- assign path_st   = block.settings.path_style | default: 'l_v_first' -%}
                {%- comment -%} Build the SVG path "d" attribute based on
                    path_style. All coordinates are in viewBox units (0-100).

                    straight: direct line from dot to description (no bend).
                    l_v_first: vertical from dot to desc_y, then horizontal
                      to desc_x. Corner at (hs_x, desc_y).
                    l_h_first: horizontal from dot to desc_x, then vertical
                      to desc_y. Corner at (desc_x, hs_y). {%- endcomment -%}
                {%- if path_st == 'l_v_first' -%}
                  {%- capture path_d -%}M {{ hs_x }} {{ hs_y }} L {{ hs_x }} {{ desc_y }} L {{ path_desc_x }} {{ desc_y }}{%- endcapture -%}
                {%- elsif path_st == 'l_h_first' -%}
                  {%- capture path_d -%}M {{ hs_x }} {{ hs_y }} L {{ path_desc_x }} {{ hs_y }} L {{ path_desc_x }} {{ desc_y }}{%- endcapture -%}
                {%- else -%}
                  {%- capture path_d -%}M {{ hs_x }} {{ hs_y }} L {{ path_desc_x }} {{ desc_y }}{%- endcapture -%}
                {%- endif -%}
                <g data-sx-sch-line="{{ block.id }}" class="sx-sch-line">
                  <path class="sx-sch-line-static" d="{{ path_d }}" stroke="#202009" stroke-width="1" fill="none" vector-effect="non-scaling-stroke" />
                  <path class="sx-sch-line-active" d="{{ path_d }}" pathLength="100" stroke="#E36E15" stroke-width="1.25" fill="none" vector-effect="non-scaling-stroke" />
                </g>
              {%- endif -%}
            {%- endfor -%}
          </svg>

          {%- comment -%} Hotspot dots, labels, panels — rendered as a separate
              loop so the SVG paths sit underneath them in z-order. {%- endcomment -%}
          {%- assign hotspot_index = 0 -%}
          {%- for block in section.blocks -%}
            {%- if block.type == 'schematic_hotspot' -%}
              {%- assign hotspot_index = hotspot_index | plus: 1 -%}
              {%- assign hs_x      = block.settings.x_pct | default: 50 -%}
              {%- assign hs_y      = block.settings.y_pct | default: 50 -%}
              {%- assign desc_x    = block.settings.desc_x_pct | default: 50 -%}
              {%- assign desc_y    = block.settings.desc_y_pct | default: 8 -%}
              {%- if desc_x == 50 and hs_x != 50 -%}
                {%- assign desc_x = hs_x -%}
              {%- endif -%}
              {%- comment -%} Same clamp as the path loop above: keep
                  desc_x within 14-86% so the 240px-wide label/panel fit
                  inside the frame, and so all three (line, label, panel)
                  use the exact same value and align perfectly. {%- endcomment -%}
              {%- if desc_x < 14 -%}
                {%- assign desc_x = 14 -%}
              {%- elsif desc_x > 86 -%}
                {%- assign desc_x = 86 -%}
              {%- endif -%}
              {%- assign hs_num    = block.settings.number | default: hotspot_index -%}
              {%- if hs_num < 10 -%}{%- assign hs_num_disp = '0' | append: hs_num -%}{%- else -%}{%- assign hs_num_disp = hs_num | append: '' -%}{%- endif -%}
              {%- comment -%} Description position determines whether the
                  description renders above or below itself in the layout.
                  We treat desc_y < 50 as "near the top" and the body should
                  flow downward from the title; desc_y >= 50 means "near the
                  bottom" and we anchor the panel above the title. This
                  matters because the title sits at desc_y and the body
                  needs to flow into available space without overlapping
                  the dot. {%- endcomment -%}
              {%- if desc_y < 50 -%}
                {%- assign hs_side = 'top' -%}
              {%- else -%}
                {%- assign hs_side = 'bottom' -%}
              {%- endif -%}

              {%- comment -%} Boundary clamping: when the description is too
                  close to a frame edge, we clamp the label and panel to a
                  fixed pixel offset from the edge instead of using desc_x%.
                  Both the label and panel get the same clamp class so they
                  stay aligned. Threshold is set so a 240px-wide element
                  centered on the edge wouldn't fit. {%- endcomment -%}
              {%- comment -%} Bare label: orange numeral + Garamond italic name.
                  Left-anchored at desc_x% — desc_x has already been clamped
                  to 14-86 above, so the label always fits within the frame
                  and lines up flush with the panel's left edge below it. {%- endcomment -%}
              <button type="button"
                      class="sx-sch-label sx-sch-label--{{ hs_side }}"
                      style="left: {{ desc_x }}%; top: {{ desc_y }}%;"
                      data-sx-sch-target="{{ block.id }}"
                      aria-expanded="false"
                      aria-controls="sx-sch-panel-{{ block.id }}">
                <span class="sx-sch-label-num">{{ hs_num_disp }}</span>
                <span class="sx-sch-label-name"><em>{{ block.settings.name | default: 'Component' }}</em></span>
              </button>

              {%- comment -%} Popout panel: hidden by default, opens on click.
                  Positioned with the same desc_x as the label so they stay
                  aligned. The Y position is offset by ~44px to sit below
                  the label's two text lines (top mode) or above the label
                  (bottom mode). {%- endcomment -%}
              <div class="sx-sch-panel sx-sch-panel--{{ hs_side }}"
                   id="sx-sch-panel-{{ block.id }}"
                   data-sx-sch-panel="{{ block.id }}"
                   style="left: {{ desc_x }}%; {% if hs_side == 'top' %}top: calc({{ desc_y }}% + 44px);{% else %}bottom: calc(100% - {{ desc_y }}% + 8px);{% endif %}"
                   role="region"
                   aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="sx-sch-panel-tech">{{ block.settings.tech | default: '' }}</div>
                <div class="sx-sch-panel-body">{{ block.settings.body | default: '' }}</div>
                <button type="button" class="sx-sch-panel-close" data-sx-sch-close="{{ block.id }}">[ CLOSE ]</button>
              </div>

              {%- comment -%} Numbered dot — sits on the photo at the component
                  location (hs_x, hs_y). {%- endcomment -%}
              <button type="button"
                      class="sx-sch-dot"
                      style="left: {{ hs_x }}%; top: {{ hs_y }}%;"
                      data-sx-sch-target="{{ block.id }}"
                      {% if block.settings.open_by_default %}data-sx-sch-default-open="true"{% endif %}
                      aria-label="{{ block.settings.name | default: 'Component' | escape }}">
                {{ hs_num_disp }}
              </button>

            {%- endif -%}
          {%- endfor -%}

          {%- comment -%} Merchant-only nudge if no hotspots are configured. {%- endcomment -%}
          {%- if hotspot_index == 0 and request.design_mode -%}
            <div class="sx-sch-no-spots">
              No schematic hotspots configured. Add up to 4 via the theme editor → "Add Schematic Hotspot".
            </div>
          {%- endif -%}

        </div>

        <div class="sx-sch-foot">
          <span>OPENSX70.COM</span>
          <span>BFC × OPENSX70</span>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    {%- comment -%} Three pillars below the schematic. Built from section
        settings so copy is editable per-product if needed. {%- endcomment -%}
    <div class="sx-sch-pillars">
      <div class="sx-sch-pillar" data-sx-sch-reveal="600">
        <span class="sx-sch-pillar-num">// 01</span>
        <div class="sx-sch-pillar-title"><em>{{ section.settings.pillar_1_title | default: 'Open source' }}</em></div>
        <p class="sx-sch-pillar-body">{{ section.settings.pillar_1_body | default: "The firmware is built and refined by a community of SX-70 obsessives. New features ship as updates, not new hardware." }}</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sx-sch-pillar" data-sx-sch-reveal="700">
        <span class="sx-sch-pillar-num">// 02</span>
        <div class="sx-sch-pillar-title"><em>{{ section.settings.pillar_2_title | default: 'Built to last' }}</em></div>
